aside.p:
We often cancel and reduce in the same step to save time and space. The book will continue to show them
separately for clarity.

	\frac{4}{6} = \frac{2 \cdot \cancel{2}}{3 \cdot \cancel{2}} = \frac{2}{3}

activity.p:
The key to reducing fractions is identifying the common factors. This is the same process as when we were
factoring polynomial expressions.

	\frac{24}{60} = \frac{2 \cdot 5}{12 \cdot 5} = \frac{2 \cdot \cancel{5}}{12 \cdot \cancel{5}} = \frac{2}{5}
	\qquad
	\frac{8 x^2 y^3}{14 xy^6}
		= \frac{4x \cdot 2xy^3}{7y^3 \cdot 2xy^3} = \frac{4x \cdot \cancel{2xy^3}}{7y^3 \cdot \cancel{2xy^3}}
		= \frac{4x}{7y^3}
